fp|3|cp|2|cs|1|ht|c|3d|3|at|{^f Convention Card: Part 2  Major Opening  }|
fp||cp|2|cs|3|ht|e|at|^b@2^*BPart 2: Major Openings ++^*N

Tonight we will do part 2 of our study "filling out the Convention Card": opening bids of 1 of a Major.

We use a few conventions and treatments playing 1 of a Major: 
In first or second seat: a 1M opening promises 5 cards or longer 
In third or 4th seat, very rarely open with a strong 4 card suit.  
Example: with   @SAx   @HAKQ10   @DQxx   @Cxxxx     open 1@h in third or 4th seat.  
You want a heart led, not a club, and if the opps overcall 1@S, you may lose the @h suit.

In the RESPONSES section:
- double raise is WEAK (alertable).  
- after overcall, double raise is WEAK. 

Conventional raise:  we check 2NT and Splinter (both alertable).
In the Other section:  Bergen Raises (some people play reverse Bergen).

1NT Forcing by unpassed hand and we check 1NT SEMI-FORCING by passed hand. 
Some people use 1NT forcing by passed hand, but I agree with Bergen here - semiforcing over a passed hand. 
What is "semi-forcing?" |
pg| ***** 5 ***** |


at| 
Essentially, if third seat opens a subminimum hand, something like  @SKJxxx   @HAxx   @Dxxx   @CQx    you will pass a semi-forcing 1NT.      You write "UPH" over forcing, "PH" over semi-forcing ( UPH = unpassed hand).

We also play 2-way reverse Drury.|
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


nt||ht|c|cp|2|at|^b@2Other treatments and understandings:  
1) a single raise is constructive, showing 3-card support and an 8-loser hand. 
2) Because we play 2 over 1 GF,  we use these CONVENTIONAL CALLS:
  a) NEW MINOR FORCING is a 1 round force and is alertable, 
  b) WEAK JUMP SHIFTS, only into majors after opening 1@C or 1@d, and always in competition;  
  c) FOURTH SUIT FORCING: my preference is to use it as game forcing. If you want to use it as 1 round force, that is 
     acceptable, but I think not as useful as game force (alertable). 
4) The auction 1@S--1NT/ 2@C--2@S shows a hand too weak to make a constructive raise. 
5) 1M - 3NT = 3334 shape, no 4-card Major, 13-15 HCP.  The reason for this response is that it defines responder's 
   hand very narrowly, and opener knows immediately whether to make a slam try.

BERGEN RAISES: A Bergen raise shows 4-card support and less than game-forcing values:  
1@S - 3@s = 0 to 6 points; 
1@S - 3@c = 7 to 9+ dummy points; 
1@S - 3@D = 10 to 12 dummy points.  I do not recommend reverse Bergen, because you are more likely to need a game 
try after a 7 to 9 point raise than after a 10 to 12 point raise.

Developments after 1@S -- 3@C:  Opener rebids 3@D as game try.  Responder signs off at 3@S with minimum hand, 
any other bid shows a MAXIMUM (8 or 9 dummy points); 
if responder bids a new suit over 3@D, it shows both a maximum and a feature (A or K). 

Developments after 1@S-- 2@S:  After a single raise, a new suit by opener is a HELP SUIT GAME TRY.  
Opener asks responder to look only at the second suit.  If responder can help avoid 3 quick losers in that suit, s/he bids game. Otherwise, sign off at 3 of the Major. 
If opener bids again after a signoff, it cancels the meaning of Help Suit.  Opener is showing a genuine 2-suiter with
extras, something like  @SKQ10xx   @hAx   @dAK109x   @Cx   where there is a good chance for slam.
Example responder raised to 2@S with:    @sAxx   @hKJxx   @DJxxx   @cxx      Now slam is at worst 50%.
The auction:   1@s - 2@s/3@D - 3@S/4@C* - 4@H* / 4NT - 5@C (RKC 1430) / 6@s  
(4@c + 4@h are Italian control bids, see later  *ICB) |
pg| ***** 7 ***** |


nt||ht|c|cp|2|at|^b@2
Self-Splinter: the auction 1@h - 2@h / 3@S (or 4@C or 4@D) shows a game-going hand, usually 6 or fewer losers AND a 
singleton or void, e.g    @sKQ10xx   @hAxx   @dAKJx   @cx 

Note the first hand had 5-5 shape, this one is 5341. By using the HSGT followed by another bid, opener can distinguish 
between strong 5521 hands, or self-splinter with strong 5431 hands.

Optional: 1@H - 2@H/ 2NT:  If opener bids 2NT after a constructive raise, responder bids his worthless short suit 
(2 or fewer cards). This allows opener to judge how well hands fit without disclosing it to the defenders. 
Example:    Kx   AK10xx   xx   AJ10x 
Since no HSGT will tell opener what she needs to know, she bids 2NT over 2@H raise. 
If responder has worthless shortness in either minor, game chances are good. 

There are many other gadgets that can be added to this structure. We did not discuss dealing with overcalls or doubles,
which are treated on the back of the card. We will deal with them later on.
This presentation represents a fairly standard treatment of Major suit bids on BBO.
If you play duplicate, this is also pretty standard among tournament players.
There are some local variations - e.g. some people use limit raises instead of Bergen, and use the 3NT bid over 1@S 
as 16-18.

Another treatment: 1@S  - 1NT / 2 any - 2NT = 10-11 (or horrible 12) HCP.
Also, very important: 1@S - 1NT / 2 any - 3NT = 16-18 HCP.
Using those treatments, responder can describe balanced hands without going past 3NT.

*ICB = Italian Control Bids. Here is how they work: 
Let's suppose that the auction begins 1@C - 1@H / 3@H. Opener has 16-18 support points and we are in a game forcing auction with Hearts as trumps. A new suit now by either partner is a control-showing bid. If the control bid is below game level, it shows first or second round control in the suit. |
pg| ***** 8 ***** |


nt||ht|c|cp|2|at|^b@2
Also, you show controls UP THE LINE. If the control bid is ABOVE game, it promises first round control. 
Here is an example:

1@c - 1@H / 3@H - 4@C shows extra values (slam try) by responder, either @CA, @CK, void or singleton (you can clarify later) 
AND since we bid controls up the line, it denies a spade control. 

Let's suppose that opener, having heard the 4@C bid, now bids 4@D, also a control bid. Since responder is known not to 
have spade control (bypassed 3@S), the 4@D bid promises a diamond control AND ALSO a spade control 
(if opener didn't have a spade control, he just stops at 4@H because spades are wide open). 

The idea of showing A or K is to discover below game level if you have more than one fast loser in a side suit. 
Key Card Blackwood will handle trump losers, so ICB's will help stay out of 33 point slams off the AK of a suit. 

