at|mitche: When declarer gets a club shift to her J, she then should play off the @CA and then a trump to dummy, followed by a club ruff.       When the outstanding clubs divide 3-3, she discards the losing @D and takes 11 tricks.
OK, let's summarize the key points from these hands:
a) If you have a hand worth bidding in first/second seat, it is to your advantage to do so. Getting the first bid in 
is a great advantage.
b) When third hand sees the opening lead, she should try to work out what the opening leader's holding is in that suit. 
Sometimes you will be able to work out the entire suit at trick 1.|
